docs.abstract: The president is embracing law enforcement, a tactic that won him support in the 2016 campaign, while ignoring calls for reform.
docs.snippet: The president is embracing law enforcement, a tactic that won him support in the 2016 campaign, while ignoring calls for reform.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump on Monday assailed a broad movement to defund police departments, invoking the kind of pro-police language that won him support with the law enforcement community in 2016 and ignoring the calls for reform that have helped shape this election.

headline.main: Trump Continues Criticism of Movement to Defund the Police
headline.print_headline: Trump Plays To Police By Blasting Defund Effort

docs.abstract: Eight weeks after the death of George Floyd, here’s a look at why longstanding protests in the city have recently intensified.
docs.snippet: Eight weeks after the death of George Floyd, here’s a look at why longstanding protests in the city have recently intensified.
docs.lead_paragraph: When a video showing George Floyd’s death in police custody spread across social media, cities and towns nationwide soon erupted in protests against systemic racism and police brutality. But while protests in many places subsided after a few weeks, Portland, Ore., has been holding demonstrations every night since May 29.The arrival of federal forces in the city this month — and concerns they were exceeding their authority and violating protesters’ rights — drew the ire of local officials and reinvigorated nightly demonstrations. With renewed force, marchers have spray-painted the walls of the U.S. District Court building, demanding that federal agents go home. Groups of mothers have banded together, locking arms and chanting: “Feds stay clear. Moms are here.”

headline.main: What Do Portland Protesters Want, and How Have the Police Responded?

byline.original: By Giulia McDonnell Nieto del Rio

docs.abstract: The image of Jen Reid, fist clenched atop the plinth in the English city where Edward Colston once stood, became a symbol of protest online. Now, it’s there in resin and steel.
docs.snippet: The image of Jen Reid, fist clenched atop the plinth in the English city where Edward Colston once stood, became a symbol of protest online. Now, it’s there in resin and steel.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Jen Reid had never marched in a Black Lives Matter protest before she took to the streets of Bristol, England, on June 7. By the end of that angry day, she had clambered up to stand in the place of a 17th-century slave trader, whose bronze statue had been pulled down and dumped in the city’s harbor.

headline.main: Statue of Black Protester Is Raised in Place of Bristol Slave Trader
headline.print_headline: Where British Slave Trader’s Statue Stood, Black Protester’s Image Rises

docs.abstract: In a state with a brutal racist history, the Black Lives Matter protests in Portland, Ore., have been overwhelmingly attended by white demonstrators.
docs.snippet: In a state with a brutal racist history, the Black Lives Matter protests in Portland, Ore., have been overwhelmingly attended by white demonstrators.
docs.lead_paragraph: PORTLAND, Ore. — Seyi Fasoranti, a chemist who moved to Oregon from the East Coast six months ago, has watched the Black Lives Matter protests in Portland with fascination. A sea of white faces in one of the whitest major American cities has cried out for racial justice every night for nearly two months.

headline.main: How One of America’s Whitest Cities Became the Center of B.L.M. Protests
headline.print_headline: Marching for Black Lives in the Whitest Big City
